antly retold. As she puts personal memories in dialogue with scholarly exegesis, Bal asks how all of these different versions complicate her own and others’ experience of the story, and how the different truths of these texts in their respective traditions illuminate the process of canonization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  atravel, traveling, history, historical, diachronic, bible, biblical, story, storytelling, memory, remembering, text, literary, reading, analysis, rape, false accusation, romance, romantic, genesis, quran, holy book, religion, religious studies, faith, belief, christian, muslim, islam, christianity, retelling, culture, cultural, tradition, canon, canonization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226035888423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226035888/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles